1) What is a shell in Linux OS? How many categories of shell exist? Why Bash is popular? 
A shell is the command-line interpreter that connects the user to the Linux operating system. It reads user commands, passes them to the kernel, and displays output. It can also run scripts to automate repetitive tasks.
Categories of shells:
1.	Bourne Shell family (sh-based):
o	sh (original Bourne shell)
o	bash (Bourne Again Shell)
o	dash (Debian Almquist Shell)
o	ksh (Korn shell)
o	zsh (Z shell)
2.	C Shell family (csh-based):
o	csh (C Shell)
o	tcsh (Tenex C Shell)
Why Bash is popular:
•	Default in almost all Linux distributions (Ubuntu, Fedora, RHEL, etc.)
•	Combines Bourne shell syntax with C-shell features.
•	Provides strong scripting capabilities, command history, auto-completion, and arrays.
•	Backward-compatible with traditional shell scripts.
•	Open source and actively maintained by GNU.
